html.body: E2F1 module The E2F1 module includes the E2F activator family of transcription E2F1, E2F2 and E2F3a as theyshare a lot of functional similarities. Dimerization between E2F1 and DP1 is stable and stimulates nuclear localization of DP1 (PMID:8832394). E2F1/DP1 is acetylated which stabilizes E2F1 protein even more (PMID:15126619). The acetylated complex is able to bind to PCAF to form an active trimer and the complex can bind to DNA on the promoter sites of its target genes. The transcriptional activity of E2F1 is increased at the G1/S transition. During G2, E2F1/DP1 is phophorylated by CycA2/CDK2, leading to dissociation followed by deacetylation and phosphorylation during S-phase for degradation. Upon DNA damage, the complex PCAF/E2F1/DP1 can be phosphorylated and stabilized either by CHEK1 and CHEK2, or by ATM and ATR (PMID:15838517; PMID:15140942), preventing E2F1 ubiquitination (PMID:15494392). E2F1 mediates the transcription of many genes involved in apoptosis. However, E2F1 transcriptional activity can also be inhibited when bound to the topoisomerase TopBP1 in order to give time to the cell to repair the damage (PMID:12697828).

Modules_begin: MODULE:E2F1 MODULE:APOPTOSIS_ENTRY Modules_end References_begin: Upon DNA damage, E2F is stabilized by ATM phosphorylation. PMID:15838517, PMID:15140942 14-3-3 tau mediates E2F1 stabilization. 14-3-3 tau interacts with ATM-phosphorylated E2F1 during DNA damage and inhibits E2F1 ubiquitination. 14-3-3 tau is also required for expression and induction of E2F1 apoptotic targets, such as p73, Apaf-1, and caspases, during DNA damage. PMID:15494392 References_end
